"step_by_step_thinking": "The patient presents with a large, tense, pruritic bulla on the inner thighs, abdomen, and lower abdomen. The skin biopsy shows an epidermal basement membrane with immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies and linear immunofluorescence. This suggests that the IgG antibodies are deposited at the basement membrane zone. In the provided documents, we can find a case of chronic bullous disease of childhood where ultrastructurally, the IgA deposits were located chiefly below the lamina basalis (the dermal type) but also, though less abundantly, in the lamina lucida. This is very much as seen in adult cases with linear IgA immune deposits at the basement membrane zone. In another document, a reappraisal of various forms of immunopathologically-mediated bullous disorders is attempted. It highlights the importance of recent advances in dermatological research and laboratory research to clinical dermatology. The investigations supply further evidence showing chronic bullous disease of childhood to be actually a counterpart of the form in adults with the same linear localization of IgA deposits. Therefore, considering these findings, it is most likely that the antibodies bind to hemidesmosomes.",
